Diagnosis. Distinguished from similar congeners (
S. guineensis
,
S. bineti
) by straight procursus ( Figs. 40 , 57 ), obtuse bulbal apophysis (
Fig. 58
), absence of median apophyses proximally on male chelicerae ( Figs. 59 , 64 ), and by strongly curved posterior margin of anterior epigynal plate ( Figs. 37 , 60 ,
73
); from
S. guineensis
also by presence of ventro-distal apophysis on procursus (
Fig. 57
), all modified hairs on large cheliceral apophyses grouped close together ( Figs. 59 , 68 ), and by pair of humps on anterior epigynal plate (
Fig. 66
); from
S. bineti
also by longer legs and by absence of dark lateral marks on carapace (only dark margins;
Fig. 34
).

Distribution. Widely distributed in southern Ivory Coast , Ghana , and Togo (
Fig. 33
). The single record from Guinea is dubious (see Notes above).
